Mechanisms of Ageing and Development
journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/mechagedev
Potential roles of Glucagon-like peptide-1 and its analogues in cognitive
impairment associated with type 2 diabetes mellitus
Zi-Wei Yu1, Rong Liu1, Xin Li, Ying Wang, Yu-Hong Fu, Hui-Yao Li, Yue Yuan, Xin-Yuan Gao*
Department of Endocrinology, First Aﬃliated Hospital of Harbin Medical University, Harbin, 150001, China
A R T I C L E I N F O
Keywords:
Cognitive impairment
Glucagon-like peptide-1
Glucagon-like peptide-1 analogues
Type 2 diabetes mellitus
A B S T R A C T
Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) is a global disease that poses a signiﬁcant threat to public health. The incidence
of both diabetes and dementia has increased simultaneously. Researchers have found that a large proportion of
dementia patients have T2DM. In recent years, increasing evidence has demonstrated a link between cognitive
decline and T2DM. Although the exact pathogenesis of cognitive impairment in T2DM is still unknown, current
studies suggest that hyperglycemia, cerebrovascular disease, brain insulin resistance, and changes in γ-amino-
butyric acid (GABAergic) neurons may mediate the association between T2DM and cognitive impairment. These
potential mechanisms may become targets for the treatment of cognitive disorders in patients with T2DM.
Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1), a widely used anti-diabetic drug, has been shown to not only eﬀectively lower
blood glucose but also improve neurological function. Previous research has conﬁrmed that GLP-1 and its
analogues are eﬀective in the treatment of cognitive impairment in patients with T2DM. This review describes
current evidence on the mechanisms underlying the association between T2DM and cognitive impairment. In
particular, this review focuses on recent advances in GLP-1 and its analogues for the treatment of T2DM-related
cognitive impairment.
1. Introduction
Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM), a worldwide epidemic, has ad-
verse eﬀects not only on the individual but also on the patient’s family
and society. Several studies have shown that the incidence of cognitive
impairment is higher in patients with T2DM compared to non-diabetic
subjects (Mehrabian et al., 2012). Cognitive impairment appears to be
an additional complication of diabetes (Biessels and Despa, 2018).
Cognitive impairment is characterized by loss of orientation, language
ability, spatial and executive function, memory, abstract thinking,
computational power, and so on. Cognitive impairment in diabetes can
be classiﬁed into three categories based on severity: diabetes-associated
cognitive decrements, mild cognitive impairment (MCI), and dementia
(Biessels and Despa, 2018). MCI is a transitional stage between normal
cognitive function and dementia characterized by cognitive impair-
ments together with intact retention of daily activities (Biessels et al.,
2014). Vascular dementia and Alzheimer’s disease (AD) are two types of
dementia that are related to diabetes. A meta-analysis based on 144
prospective studies elucidated that diabetes increases the risk of MCI by
1.49 times and the risk of dementia by 1.43–1.91 times (Xue et al.,
2019). In addition, diabetes accelerates the development of MCI into
dementia. Recently, research from Korea reported that the prevalence
of MCI in T2DM patients was 32.7 % (Lee et al., 2014). The annual
incidence of progression from MCI to AD in T2DM patients is between 6
% and 25 %, compared with 0.2–3.9 % in the general population of the
same age (Van den Berg et al., 2005).
Since T2DM has been conﬁrmed to increase the risk of cognitive
impairment, early therapeutic interventions for patients with T2DM
may reduce the occurrence and delay the development of cognitive
impairment, thus improving patient quality of life and life expectancy.
Glucagon-like peptide 1 (GLP-1) is a 30 amino acid long gut-secreted
peptide that can reduce glucose levels and weight by stimulating insulin
secretion and inhibiting glucagon release (Holst, 2007). Therefore, GLP-
1 and its analogues are currently the main treatments for T2DM and
obesity. In recent years, increasing attention has been paid to the pro-
tective eﬀect of GLP-1 and its analogues on the central nervous system.
A previous study demonstrated that GLP-1 receptor knockout (GLP-
1r−/−) mice, which exhibit hyperglycemia, have signiﬁcantly im-
paired synaptic plasticity and cognitive function, including an inability
to distinguish between new and familiar objects (Abbas et al., 2009).
Further studies have shown that GLP-1 receptor agonists can rapidly
induce long-term potentiation of synaptic transmission (LTP), thus
