improving synaptic activity (Abbas et al., 2009; Bak et al., 2011).
Moreover, GLP-1 receptor agonists have also been shown to increase
the spontaneous ﬁring rate of hippocampal neurons (Abbas et al.,
2009). Thus, GLP-1 plays an important role in protecting synaptic
plasticity and cognitive function. Interestingly, researchers have also
found that GLP-1 and its analogues can alleviate the symptoms of pa-
tients with AD (Gejl et al., 2017).
This review introduces the mechanisms of T2DM-related cognitive
impairment and provides the latest evidence on the potential eﬀects of
GLP-1 and its analogues on cognitive impairment in patients with
T2DM.
2. Underlying mechanisms of cognitive impairment in T2DM
2.1. Cerebrovascular disease and neurodegenerative changes
Cerebrovascular disease is considered to be a risk factor for cogni-
tive impairment in T2DM. Previous studies have conﬁrmed that, com-
pared to people without diabetes, diabetic patients with decreased
memory capacity have lower white matter tract volumes (Van Bussel
et al., 2016) and white matter hyperintensities (WMH) on magnetic
resonance imaging (MRI) (Reijmer et al., 2013). WMH can increase the
risk of cerebral microvascular hemorrhage in patients with T2DM
(Biessels and Despa, 2018). White matter disease and cerebral infarcts
are considered to be marks of cerebrovascular diseases (Luchsinger,
2012). Cerebrovascular diseases reduce cerebral blood ﬂow; the hip-
pocampus and temporal lobes are sensitive to ischemia, resulting in
decreased cognitive function (Yuan and Wang, 2017).
Notably, research suggests that neurodegenerative changes, rather
than cerebrovascular disease, are important contributors to cognitive
impairment in T2DM (Groeneveld et al., 2018). MRI results indicate the
presence of structural atrophy in the brains of T2DM patients (Biessels
and Reijmer, 2014). Functional MRI results have also revealed reduced
functional connectivity among cognitive networks in the brains of
T2DM patients (Zhang et al., 2016). However, the speciﬁc structures
and types of nerve cells that are damaged in the brains of T2DM pa-
tients have not been precisely determined. Researchers have also found
signiﬁcant abnormalities in the microstructure of the left hemisphere of
T2DM patients, particularly
in the hippocampus and the para-
hippocampal gyrus (Yau et al., 2014). The hippocampus is related to
human memory and spatial location. On the other hand, one study
reported that the β-amyloid (Aβ) level in the hippocampus of strepto-
zocin (STZ)-induced diabetic rats was 2.9 times that of normal rats (Liu
et al., 2008).
Rapid advances in imaging technologies have provided visual evi-
dence for a link between T2DM and cognitive impairment, indicating
that cognitive decline in patients with T2DM may be mediated by
cerebrovascular disease and neurodegenerative changes. Importantly,
further research is still necessary to identify the speciﬁc damage to
brain structures and neurons that underlies cognitive impairment in
T2DM.
2.2. Hyperglycemia and hypoglycemia
Hyperglycemia is associated with cognitive impairment. In a pro-
spective study of older adults living in the community, researchers
found a J-type association between hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c) and MCI.
Following this, they conducted a ﬁve-year follow-up study of people
aged 66–90 years and found that hyperglycemia was related to de-
creased cognitive function (Rawlings et al., 2019). Similarly, another
clinical trial of MCI patients, with an average follow-up duration of
3.5 ± 1.1 years, showed that HbA1c ≥5.9 % was associated with
double the risk of MCI (Wang et al., 2017). Interestingly, another study
reported that higher HbA1c was associated with cognitive dysfunction
in T2DM patients (Cukierman-Yaﬀe et al., 2009). Further, a clinical
study showed that advanced glycation end products (AGEs) and the
receptor for advanced glycation end products (RAGE) were increased in
T2DM patients with MCI compared to T2DM patients with normal
cognitive function (Gorska-Ciebiada et al., 2015). Chronic exposure to
high glucose leads to enhanced formation of AGEs and RAGE, which has
potentially toxic eﬀects on neurons (Valente et al., 2010). Furthermore,
chronic hyperglycemia in the brain not only promotes β-site cleavage of
the Aβ precursor protein but also triggers intracellular tau hyper-
phosphorylation and synaptic loss (Guo et al., 2016). Thus, good
management of blood glucose is a simple and eﬀective way to prevent
and improve cognitive impairment.
T2DM patients are prone to hypoglycemia. A cohort study found
that patients with T2DM with a history of hypoglycemia were at in-
creased risk of cognitive impairment and dementia, suggesting that
hypoglycemia is closely associated with cognitive decline (Lee et al.,
2018). A large body of animal model-based evidence also provides
strong support for this potential relationship. For instance, researchers
have observed neuronal death and oxidative damage in the hippo-
campus of rats with acute/severe (A/S) hypoglycemia. In addition,
microglial activation has been observed in the brains of these rats.
These changes occur because hypoglycemia causes excessive activation
of poly (ADP-ribose) polymerase-1 (PARP-1), which further consumes
cytoplasmic nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+), resulting in
energy exhaustion (Won et al., 2012a). Pyruvate and lactate have been
shown to reduce neuronal death by inhibiting PARP-1, thus improving
cognitive impairment (Suh et al., 2005; Won et al., 2012a). Recurrent/
moderate (R/M) hypoglycemia has also been found to cause neuronal
death and oxidative damage in the hippocampus of rats, leading to
cognitive impairment (Languren et al., 2019). Another study further
conﬁrmed that oxidative damage in the hippocampus of diabetic rats is
more serious than that of non-diabetic rats after hypoglycemia (Won
et al., 2012b). Therefore, oxidative stress is another important me-
chanism underlying cognitive impairment induced by hypoglycemia. In
short, hypoglycemia may lead to cognitive decline through multiple
pathways. Strict monitoring of the blood glucose levels of diabetic pa-
tients is particularly important.
2.3. Brain insulin resistance
It is now agreed that brain insulin resistance is an important pa-
thophysiological mechanism underlying cognitive impairment in T2DM
(Kullmann et al., 2016; Spinelli et al., 2019). To date, researchers have
primarily used neuroimaging techniques (e.g., functional MRI and PET)
to observe the action of insulin in the human brain in order to evaluate
the presence or absence of brain insulin resistance (Kullmann et al.,
2016). Several researchers regard insulin as a cognitive modulator.
Moreover, there are high levels of insulin receptors in the hippocampus.
An early study showed that insulin levels in the hippocampus were
signiﬁcantly increased during learning and memory (McNay et al.,
2010). However, when insulin resistance is present in the hippocampus,
severe cognitive impairments can occur (McNay et al., 2006).
Insulin signaling plays a signiﬁcant role in maintaining normal
cognitive function. Thus, impaired insulin signaling may cause cogni-
tive deﬁcits. Phosphorylation of insulin receptor substrate-1 (IRS-1)
proteins on serine residues has emerged as a key step in the inhibition
of insulin signaling under both physiological and pathological condi-
tions (Boura-Halfon and Zick, 2009). At the same time, insulin re-
sistance decreases the activity of Jun N-terminal kinase (JNK) and ac-
celerates the serine phosphorylation of IRS-1 (Benedict and Grillo,
2018). IRS-1 then inhibits the phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K)/Akt
signaling pathways, thereby regulating downstream factors such as
glycogen synthase kinase-3β (GSK-3β) and mammalian target of rapa-
mycin (mTOR) (Green et al., 2019; Rahman et al., 2019). Down-regu-
lated Akt leads to GSK-3βactivation by the dephosphorylation of GSK-3,
which triggers tau hyperphosphorylation (Hegde et al., 2019). The
phosphorylated tau is polymerized into linear double helical ﬁlaments
called neuroﬁbrillary tangles. Loss of normal tau protein function leads
