Mechanisms of Ageing and Development 190 (2020) 111294
2
to pathological cytoskeletal disturbances. This, in turn, aﬀects normal
neurological functions, such as axonal transport and maintenance of
proper morphology, resulting in neurodegeneration and synaptic dys-
function (Barage and Sonawane, 2015). In addition, the PI3K/Akt/
mTOR pathway, which plays an important role in protecting the sur-
vival and growth of dendritic spines, is inhibited by insulin resistance
(Rahman et al., 2019). The mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK)/
extracellular signal-regulated kinases (ERK) signaling pathway is also
an important component of the insulin signaling pathway, and is in-
volved in the promotion of synaptic growth and nerve cell repair (Green
et al., 2019; Palleria et al., 2016) (Fig. 1).
Insulin resistance exists in the hippocampus and cerebellar cortex of
AD patients, accompanied by insulin-like growth factors-1 (IGF-1) re-
sistance (Talbot et al., 2012). IGF-1, which is structurally similar to
insulin, binds to the IGF-1 receptor (IGF-1R) to activate IRS-2, and
subsequently, enhances insulin signaling, thereby preventing apoptosis,
promoting proliferation and diﬀerentiation of nerve cells, and pro-
tecting cognitive function (Rui-Hua et al., 2019; Yang et al., 2018).
Therefore, IGF-1 resistance also induces cognitive impairment by de-
stroying insulin signaling. Insulin degrading enzyme (IDE) degrades a
number of physiological peptides, including insulin and Aβ (Hegde
et al., 2019). When insulin resistance leads to excessive levels of insulin,
IDE causes an increase in decomposition of insulin and a decrease in
decomposition of Aβ, thus causing Aβ accumulation (Benedict and
Grillo, 2018). Accumulation of Aβ increases intracellular Ca2+
loading, inducing oxidative stress and neurodegeneration (Barage and
Sonawane, 2015). Several clinical studies have also conﬁrmed that in-
sulin resistance is an independent risk factor for MCI and for the pro-
gression of MCI to AD (Kim et al., 2015). Hence, insulin resistance is an
important factor implicated in cognitive decline in patients with dia-
betes.
2.4. γ-aminobutyric acid (GABAergic) neurons
The relationship between the nervous system and diabetes is con-
centrated in the hippocampus, but the nature of the damage to speciﬁc
brain structures and types of neuronal cells is not yet fully elucidated.
One study showed that glutamate decarboxylase (GAD), which is the
major enzyme responsible for GABA synthesis, was decreased in the
medial prefrontal cortex of STZ-induced rats (Castillo-Gómez et al.,
2015). Other studies have reported that age-related cognitive decline is
associated with dysfunction of GABAergic neurons (Kann, 2016;
McQuail et al., 2015) and increased susceptibility to metabolic stress
(Kann, 2016). Approximately 5–10 % of the neocortex and striatal
populations of neurons are GABAergic interneurons, which play an
important regulatory role in the normal functioning of these structures
(Lovett-Barron and Losonczy, 2014). The neocortex and striatum are
important for cognition and sensorimotor functions. Further, diﬀer-
ences in GABAergic interneurons in the piriform cortex (Lietzau et al.,
2016) and hippocampus (Larsson et al., 2016; Yi, 2013) of diabetic rats
have been reported. Together, these ﬁndings suggest that there is a
connection between the GABAergic system and diabetes. Cognitive
impairment in T2DM may be associated with reduced GABA. Further
studies are required to verify this assertion.
One study examined changes in cortical and striatal glutamic acid-
(GAD), calbindin- (CB), parvalbumin- (PV), and calretinin-(CR)positive
GABAergic neurons in T2DM rats using immunohistochemistry and
quantitative microscopy. This study reported that CB-positive neurons
were signiﬁcantly decreased in the neocortex and striatum of middle-
aged Goto-Kakizaki (GK) (a model of spontaneous T2DM) rats. There
was also a signiﬁcant reduction in neurite branching in the neocortex of
these rats. The density of GAD-positive cells was also reduced in the
striatum in GK rats. The volume of PV-positive neurons in the striatum
was also increased in GK rats (Larsson et al., 2016). CB is expressed in
inhibitory interneurons in the cerebral cortex and plays an important
role in the time coordination of pyramidal cell output. Thus, there may
be impaired modulation of cortical excitatory circuits in GK rats. This is
probably the cause of early cognitive impairment in GK rats. In GK rats,
the reduction in CB-positive neurons might interrupt calcium home-
ostasis in the striatum, thus aﬀecting the normal function of these cells.
Previous studies have conﬁrmed that CB mRNA decreases in some brain
structures with aging and is decreased in various neurodegenerative
diseases (Riascos et al., 2014). The decrease in GABA in the striatum of
middle-aged GK rats may indicate that the overall inhibitory activity of
the structure is decreased. Martin Larsson et al. speculated that the
increase in PV interneuron volume may be a compensatory mechanism
to balance the likely decrease in GABAergic inhibitory signaling under
T2DM (Larsson et al., 2016). Further, some scholars have proposed that
cognitive and memory impairments are associated with gamma oscil-
lations in hippocampal neuronal networks. Cognitive impairment leads
to increased PV-expressing interneuron (PV + IN) density and gamma
