postsynaptic potentials (Lietzau et al., 2017). Examining changes in
nerves and neurotransmitters in the brain not only provides insight into
the mechanisms of cognitive impairment in diabetes, but also provides
potential new methods for the prevention and treatment of diabetes.
It is clear that the mechanisms underlying cognitive impairment are
not completely elucidated. More research on the development process
and risk factors for diabetes are required. Such research should be a
priority in order to reduce the incidence of cognitive impairment in
patients with T2DM.
3. GLP-1 in T2DM-related cognitive impairment
GLP-1, a hormone released by intestinal L cells, lowers blood glu-
cose by stimulating pancreatic B cells to release insulin (Grieco et al.,
2019). Given the short half-life of natural GLP-1, GLP-1 analogues such
as liraglutide and exenatide (a synthetic form of exendin-4) are cur-
rently used to treat obesity and T2DM (Talbot, 2014). GLP-1 and GLP-1
analogues not only act on pancreatic islets but also protect and nourish
neurons by entering the blood-brain barrier. This eﬀect is mainly
mediated by activation of the cAMP second messenger pathway caused
by the binding of GLP-1 and GLP-1 receptors, which are widely dis-
tributed in the brain (Bak et al., 2011). There is growing evidence that
GLP-1 and its analogues can alleviate the symptoms of cognitive im-
pairment and AD through various mechanisms.
3.1. Preclinical studies
Several scholars have reported that diabetes can lead to a break-
down of the blood-brain barrier and disorder of the brain environment;
this may be an important mechanism underlying the development of
cognitive impairment (VanGilder et al., 2009). In diabetic rats, damage
to the blood-brain barrier and blood-cerebrospinal ﬂuid barrier, in-
cluding reduced proteins and permeability, leads to neuronal degen-
eration and cognitive dysfunction. Exendin-4 can reverse alterations in
proteins and brain barrier permeability, thereby improving cognitive
function (Zanotto et al., 2017). Cerebrovascular disease is also con-
sidered to be a risk factor for cognitive impairment in T2DM. In a model
of cerebral ischemia/reperfusion injury in diabetic rats, researchers
found that recombinant human glucagon-like peptide 1 (rhGLP-1)
could not only control blood glucose but also reduced the volume of
cerebral infarcts and improved neurological function. This eﬀect may
be related to inhibition of apoptosis and oxidative stress (Fang et al.,
2018).
In the above section on brain insulin resistance, we mentioned that
insulin receptors have neuroprotective eﬀects. These neuroprotective
eﬀects include decreased inﬂammation, apoptosis, and tau phosphor-
ylation, increased synaptic plasticity, and promotion of neuronal
growth. Insulin receptor activation is able to decrease synaptic binding
sites through the decreased toxic activity of amyloid oligomers, re-
sulting in a reduction in oxidative stress and dendritic spines loss (De
Felice et al., 2009). Brain insulin resistance is an important pathoge-
netic feature observed in AD, and is mainly mediated by impaired in-
sulin signaling. Liraglutide can reverse the decrease in insulin receptors
and the damage to synapses via activation of cAMP/PKA signaling to
improve cognitive function (Batista et al., 2018). One study found that
liraglutide was eﬀective in reversing cognitive impairment and pre-
venting ultrastructural damage in AD-like model mice. This is probably
because it reduces tau phosphorylation in the brain by regulating the
PI3K/Akt/GSK-3β signaling pathway (Qi et al., 2017). Interestingly,
both the novel GLP-1/glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide
(GIP) dual agonist and the GLP-1/GIP/Gcg triagonist target GSK-3β to
better improve cognitive function, compared with using GLP-1 alone
(Cao et al., 2018; Li et al., 2018). Moreover, a study of hippocampus
cells of AD mice showed that GLP-1 increased Akt and ERK1/2 phos-
phorylation and protected cells from death induced by Aβ, oxidative
stress, and endoplasmic reticulum stress. It has been suggested that the
neuroprotective eﬀect of GLP-1 against AD-associated stressors is
achieved by the activation of proteins associated with cellular survival
(Yoshino et al., 2015). The above evidence demonstrates that GLP-1
and its analogues can contribute to improved cognitive function by
improving the insulin signaling pathway in AD mouse models. At the
same time, these ﬁndings highlight the potential for the use of GLP-1
and its analogues in the treatment of cognitive impairment in T2DM
(Fig. 1).
T2DM is accompanied by impaired insulin signaling, which in turn,
is associated with cognitive decline. Researchers have demonstrated
that exendin-4 can improve learning and memory function in diabetes-
related AD rat models and pathological studies have further demon-
strated that exendin-4 reduces degeneration of hippocampal neurons.
