hyperpho-
sphorylation by decreasing GSK-3βactivity (Chen et al., 2012). Another
study reported decreased glutamate levels in the hippocampus of STZ-
induced diabetic mice. Exendin-4 can reverse the dysfunction of glu-
tamate uptake by aﬀecting the PI3K signaling pathway, thereby de-
laying the progression of cognitive impairment in diabetic mice
(Zanotto et al., 2019). Thus, GLP-1 and GLP-1 analogues can also im-
prove cognitive dysfunction by targeting insulin signaling in diabetic
animal models. On the other hand, insulin resistance can cause the
deposition of Aβ, which is the main pathological feature of AD. Li et al.
(2010) found high levels of AβPP and Aβ in triple transgenic AD (3xTg-
AD) mice with STZ-induced diabetes. In addition, these authors found
that exendin-4 could signiﬁcantly reduce AβPP and Aβ in mouse models
(Li et al., 2010). In summary, GLP-1 and its analogues can play a po-
sitive role in cognitive impairment by improving insulin resistance in
both AD animal models and STZ-induced diabetic animal models.
Another study showed that GLP-1 and exendin-4 enhance GABA
signaling in the hippocampus through presynaptic and postsynaptic
mechanisms (Korol et al., 2015). Unlike GLP-1 and exendin-4, liraglu-
tide can only regulate GABAergic signaling in the hippocampus through
a presynaptic mechanism (Babateen et al., 2017). In section 2.4, we
mentioned that the density of CB-positive GABAergic neurons in the
striatum of GK rats was decreased, thus aﬀecting cognitive function.
Exendin-4 has been found to increase the density of GABAergic neu-
rons, thus reversing this negative eﬀect (Larsson et al., 2016).
The above evidence indicates that GLP-1 and its analogues can
improve cognitive impairment by targeting signal transduction path-
ways, pathological mechanisms, and GABAergic interneurons. These
studies provide a strong theoretical basis for the clinical feasibility of
GLP-1 and its analogues in the treatment of cognitive dysfunction in
patients with T2DM.
3.2. Clinical trials
A 26-week placebo-controlled, double-blind clinical trial in patients
with AD indicated that liraglutide increases glucose metabolism in the
brain,
thus
delaying
the
development
of
cognitive
disorders.
Surprisingly, however, GLP-1 did not have an eﬀect on the elimination
of Aβ accumulation in this study (Gejl et al., 2016). In contrast, in
another 12-week double-blinded, placebo-controlled study targeting
individuals with normal cognition but with subjective cognitive com-
plaints, no signiﬁcant diﬀerence in cognitive function was observed
between the placebo group and the liraglutide group after 12 weeks
(Watson et al., 2019). This contradiction may be due to the diﬀerent
research objects and treatment durations in these two studies. None-
theless, these ﬁndings have inspired clinicians and epidemiologists to
study the therapeutic role of GLP-1 in cognitive impairment in patients
with T2DM.
A nested case-control study indicated that GLP-1 analogues reduce
the risk of dementia in people with T2DM (Wium-Andersen et al.,
2019). Another study reported that after 3 months of GLP-1 receptor
agonist therapy, activation of the right hippocampus was enhanced and
cognitive function was improved in obese patients with T2DM who
Z.-W. Yu, et al.
Mechanisms of Ageing and Development 190 (2020) 111294
4
showed cognitive impairment (Zhang et al., 2019). Similarly, a rando-
mized controlled study based on obese patients with pre-diabetes or
early T2DM also conﬁrmed that liraglutide can alleviate memory da-
mage in diabetic patients in the early stage of the disease (Vadini et al.,
2005). (Table 1).
In short, current research on humans is very limited. Therefore,
more clinical trials are needed to demonstrate the reliability and safety
of GLP-1 in the treatment of cognitive dysfunction in T2DM patients.
4. Conclusions
Cognitive impairment severely aﬀects daily functioning and the
quality of life of patients. At present, there is signiﬁcant evidence of
cognitive impairment in diabetic patients. T2DM-related cognitive im-
pairment has become a research hotspot; however, the mechanisms
underlying this cognitive impairment are not fully elucidated. GLP-1
and its analogues are widely used in clinical practice as new anti-dia-
betic drugs. At present, a large number of animal studies have de-
monstrated that GLP-1 and its analogues can eﬀectively delay the de-
velopment of cognitive impairment. However, there remains a lack of
clinical trials to further clarify the eﬀect of GLP-1 on cognitive im-
pairment. This review has discussed the potential mechanisms of cog-
nitive impairment in T2DM and the eﬀects of GLP-1 and its analogues
on cognitive impairment. GLP-1 and its analogues may prove useful in
the treatment of cognitive impairment and dementia in patients with
T2DM.
